Follow-up to #78508. In x/net v0.55.0, server_wrap.go (build tag `go1.27 && !http2legacy`) replaces server.go's configureServer with a thinner version that omits the NextProtos side-effect callers depend on. The legacy server.go configureServer nil-inits s.TLSConfig and appends "h2" and "http/1.1" to s.TLSConfig.NextProtos at lines 205-209; the wrap version does neither.

As a result, any caller using http2.ConfigureServer to set up h2 on an http.Server and then serving TLS — for instance combined with httptest.Server.StartTLS, or with a manual tls.Listen — ends up with an http/1.1-only or empty ALPN list. Clients requesting h2 fail the TLS handshake with "remote error: tls: no application protocol", and the server logs "tls: client requested unsupported application protocols ([\"h2\"])".

This surfaced in Kubernetes once Go tip began identifying as go1.27, breaking ci-kubernetes-unit-golang-tip; tracking at kubernetes/kubernetes#139263.

Suggested fix: in server_wrap.go's configureServer, mirror the corresponding block from server.go. strSliceContains lives in transport.go which is also gated to the legacy build tag, so the wrap path needs slices.Contains instead. Adds imports for crypto/tls and slices plus ten lines:

```go
if s.TLSConfig == nil {
    s.TLSConfig = new(tls.Config)
}
if !slices.Contains(s.TLSConfig.NextProtos, NextProtoTLS) {
    s.TLSConfig.NextProtos = append(s.TLSConfig.NextProtos, NextProtoTLS)
}
if !slices.Contains(s.TLSConfig.NextProtos, "http/1.1") {
    s.TLSConfig.NextProtos = append(s.TLSConfig.NextProtos, "http/1.1")
}
```

